    <title>Combined summary - DNS seeds returning gone peers</title>
    <updated>2023-06-04T17:38:56.956223+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2011-August/000271.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin network is experiencing a major issue with a lack of connectable slots, which is causing a slowdown in peer bringup for Android apps. Out of 48 IPs returned by the DNS seeds, only 19 are actually usable, and six are closed. Currently, there is no address-saving functionality for last-used peers in the Android apps, which needs fixing.To resolve this issue, a custom DNS server that watches the network to find long-lived peers running the latest version could be helpful. The developers suggest sorting nodes by version, how long they've been observed to exist, and the last polling time to better manage connectivity. Matt Corallo suggested using https://github.com/TheBlueMatt/dnsseed but recommended cleaning it up or using a different DNS server that pulls directly from the database in a more dynamic way. Mike Hearn discussed the possibility of finding a friend to take on DNS seeding as a project, and Rick Wesson expressed interest in contributing to the project.In addition to the DNS seeder issue, bad nodes appearing in the DNS seeds are causing problems for Android apps. The developers discuss different DNS servers and non-blocking network stacks to improve connectivity and stability within the Bitcoin network. However, they also express concerns about ISPs caching DNS for too long and whether current settings for slots were too conservative.Furthermore, the discussion also touches on the topic of limited slots and whether current settings are too conservative. While increasing anti-Denial of Service (DoS) limits in version 0.4 was suggested by some, others argued that it risked running nodes on lower memory systems out of memory. Although anti-DoS limits were redone in version 0.24, the issue persisted, and a solution was needed. Overall, the conversation focuses on finding ways to improve connectivity and stability within the Bitcoin network while avoiding plagiarism when summarizing the discussion.</summary>
